{{nihongo|Tokoyo|常世|}}.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |title=Encyclopedia of Shinto詳細 |url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=8740 |access-date=2023-03-10 |website=國學院大學デジタルミュージアム |language=ja}}</ref>, also known as {{nihongo|Unseen world|隠世、幽世|Kakuriyo}},<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |title=隠り世(かくりよ)と現世（うつしよ）、隠り世ってどんなところ？ - waqwaq |url=https://waqwaq-j.com/japan/1093/ |access-date=2022-12-22 |website=waqwaq-j.com}}</ref> or Taikaikan<ref>{{Cite web |date=2018-02-19 |title=國學院デジタルミュージアム |url=http://web.archive.org/web/20180219090216/http://k-amc.kokugakuin.ac.jp/DM/detail.do?class_name=col_eos&data_id=23640 |access-date=2023-03-10 |website=web.archive.org}}</ref> is a world in [[shinto]] which never changes<ref name=":1" /> it denotes the "other world."<ref name=":4" /> It is believed to be a place where various kami and spirits of ancestors live.<ref name=":4" />
In this world people have [[eternal youth]].<ref name=":4" /> There are two main related terms {{nihongo|Tokoyo|常世|}} and {{nihongo|2=隠世、幽世|3=Kakuriyo}}
Tokoyo can be located in various places such as in a foreign land, under the sea, in heaven, under the ground, or in a place beyond the ocean.<ref name=":4" />
In ancient times, Tokoyo was seen as a utopia of eternal youth, long life, bounteous wealth, and pleasure across the sea.<ref name=":4" />
Tokoyo can also be interpreted as the land of the dead or the nether worlds.<ref name=":4" />
Various episodes related to Tokoyo can be found in classics such as Kojiki and Nihongi.<ref name=":4" /> including [[Tajimamori]] going to Tokoyo in the reign of [[Emperor Suinin]] to help him become immortal<ref name=":4" />, and in the reign of [[Empress Kogyoku]] a fanatical cult dedicated to the god of Tokoyo emerging<ref name=":4" />
[[Motoori Norinaga]] categorized three types of Tokoyo: a world of perpetual darkness, a world where people never grew old, and a world across the sea.<ref name=":4" />
== Identification with Mount Penglai == {{Main|Mount Penglai}} In the story of [[Urashima Tarō]] Tokoyo is identified with [[Mount Penglai]].{{efn|It is written as Horai ([[Mount Penglai]]) in the straight Chinese text, but it is also annotated to indicate its should be read as [[Tokoyo]]-no-kuni.}}{{sfnp|McKeon|1996|pp=34, 65}}<ref name="poulton">{{citation |last=Poulton |first=M. Cody |title=Spirits of Another Sort: The Plays of Izumi Kyōka |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3TlkAAAAMAAJ |page=88 |year=2001 |publisher=Center for Japanese Studies, the University of Michigan |isbn=9780939512010}}</ref>
The Asteroid [[162173 Ryugu]] has two [[fossae]] named after each one.<ref>https://www.aanda.org/articles/aa/pdf/2020/07/aa37096-19.pdf</ref> [[simple:Tokoyo]]
