{{refimprove|date=December 2022}}

{{nihongo|Tokoyo|常世|}}.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |title=Encyclopedia of Shinto詳細 |url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=8740 |access-date=2023-03-10 |website=國學院大學デジタルミュージアム |language=ja}}</ref>, also known as {{nihongo|Unseen world|隠世、幽世|Kakuriyo}},<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |title=隠り世(かくりよ)と現世（うつしよ）、隠り世ってどんなところ？ - waqwaq |url=https://waqwaq-j.com/japan/1093/ |access-date=2022-12-22 |website=waqwaq-j.com}}</ref> or Taikaikan<ref>{{Cite web |date=2018-02-19 |title=國學院デジタルミュージアム |url=http://k-amc.kokugakuin.ac.jp/DM/detail.do?class_name=col_eos&data_id=23640 |access-date=2023-03-10 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20180219090216/http://k-amc.kokugakuin.ac.jp/DM/detail.do?class_name=col_eos&data_id=23640 |archive-date=2018-02-19 }}</ref> is realm in Shinto. It is an "[[otherworld]]"<ref name=":4" /> but not necessarily seen as a place in the afterlife, but rather as a mythical realm with many interpretations.

It denotes the "other world."<ref name=":4" /> It is believed to be a place where various kami and spirits of ancestors live.<ref name=":4" /> 

In this world people have [[eternal youth]].<ref name=":4" /> There are two main related terms {{nihongo|Tokoyo|常世|}} and {{nihongo|2=隠世、幽世|3=Kakuriyo}}

Tokoyo can be located in various places such as in a foreign land, under the sea, in heaven, under the ground, or in a place beyond the ocean.<ref name=":4" />

In ancient times, Tokoyo was seen as a utopia of eternal youth, long life, bounteous wealth, and pleasure across the sea.<ref name=":4" />

Tokoyo can also be interpreted as the land of the dead or the nether worlds.<ref name=":4" />

Various episodes related to Tokoyo can be found in classics such as Kojiki and Nihongi.<ref name=":4" /> including [[Tajimamori]] going to Tokoyo in the reign of [[Emperor Suinin]] to help him become immortal<ref name=":4" />, and in the reign of [[Empress Kogyoku]] a fanatical cult dedicated to the god of Tokoyo emerging<ref name=":4" />

[[Motoori Norinaga]] categorized three types of Tokoyo: a world of perpetual darkness, a world where people never grew old, and a world across the sea.<ref name=":4" />

[[Ne-no-kuni]] is sometimes considered to be identical to Tokoyo no Kuni, or alternatively [[Yomi]] the underworld.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |title=根の国 |url=https://kotobank.jp/word/根の国-595461 |access-date=2018-02-18 |website={{lang|ja|日本大百科全書}} at kotobank.jp}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite book |last=Bonnefoy |first=Yves |title=Asian Mythologies |last2=Doniger |first2=Wendy |publisher=University of Chicago Press |year=1991 |isbn=0-226-06456-5 |pages=270-271}}</ref> There is no clear consensus on the relationship between these three realms.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":2" />

== Myth of Okuninushi ==
{{Main|Ōkuninushi}}
In the [[Kojiki]] Ōkuninushi used to rule the world, but he relinquished control during the [[Kuni-yuzuri]] or transfer of control to the [[Amatsukami]]. He made a request that [[Izumo-taisha|a magnificent palace]] – rooted in the earth and reaching up to heaven – be built in his honor, he withdrew himself into the "less-than-one-hundred eighty-road-bendings" (百不足八十坰手 ''momotarazu yasokumade'', i.e. the unseen world of the spirit) and disappeared from the physical realm.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Philippi |first1=Donald L. |title=Kojiki |date=2015 |publisher=Princeton University Press |pages=129–136}}</ref><ref>Chamberlain (1882). [http://sacred-texts.com/shi/kj/kj039.htm Section XXXII.—Abdication of the Deity Master-of-the-Great-Land.]</ref>

== Identification with Mount Penglai ==
{{Main|Mount Penglai}}
In the story of [[Urashima Tarō]] Tokoyo is identified with [[Mount Penglai]].{{efn|It is written as Horai ([[Mount Penglai]]) in the straight Chinese text, but it is also annotated to indicate its should be read as [[Tokoyo]]-no-kuni.}}{{sfnp|McKeon|1996|pp=34, 65}}<ref name="poulton">{{citation |last=Poulton |first=M. Cody |title=Spirits of Another Sort: The Plays of Izumi Kyōka |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3TlkAAAAMAAJ |page=88 |year=2001 |publisher=Center for Japanese Studies, the University of Michigan |isbn=9780939512010}}</ref>

The Asteroid [[162173 Ryugu]] has two [[fossae]] named after each one.<ref>https://www.aanda.org/articles/aa/pdf/2020/07/aa37096-19.pdf</ref>
[[simple:Tokoyo]]

== In popular culture ==
It features as the setting of [[Kakuriyo: Bed and Breakfast for Spirits]]

